posts.raw_content:
Based on a review of reports from the U.S. Chemical Safety and Hazard Investigation Board (CSB), Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA), news archives, and industry analyses, there have been at least 12 documented refinery explosions in the United States from October 2015 to October 2025. This count focuses specifically on incidents at oil refineries (facilities that process crude oil into fuels and petrochemicals) involving explosions, distinct from mere fires, leaks, or non-refinery petrochemical plant blasts.  
The frequency of such incidents has increased in recent years, with analyses showing a threefold rise in refinery fires and explosions in Texas and Louisiana (key refining hubs) from 2018–2022 compared to the prior five years. Many stem from equipment failures, corrosion, or procedural lapses, often in aging facilities (average U.S. refinery age: ~40 years). Casualties and evacuations vary, but no single event since 2005 has matched the scale of the 2005 BP Texas City disaster (15 deaths).
